Scoring Criteria
Match Score (0-100)
95-100: All required skills + nice-to-have skills + exceeds experience requirements
85-94: All required skills + meets experience requirements
75-84: Most required skills + partial experience
60-74: Some required skills + limited experience
Below 60: Few matching skills or insufficient experience
Interest Score (0-100)
90-100: Strong excitement, immediately available, eager to discuss
75-89: Genuine interest, wants to learn more about role/team
60-74: Moderate interest, some questions or concerns
Below 60: Low interest, not actively looking, or unavailable
 Ranking Methodology
Final Ranking = (Match Score + Interest Score) / 2

Candidates are sorted by combined score in descending order. The dashboard displays:

Combined score (ranking position)
Individual Match and Interest scores with visual progress bars
Color coding: Green (≥80), Yellow (60-79), Red (<60)


Trade-offs
Trade-off	Rationale
LLM-based matching vs. strict filtering	Used LLMs for flexible, semantic matching rather than rigid keyword filters. Trade-off: slightly higher latency and cost, but better recall on qualified candidates who don't use exact keywords.
Simulated interest assessment	Instead of actually emailing candidates, the agent simulates a conversation to predict interest. Trade-off: not real-world validation, but enables rapid prototyping without spam risk.
Google Sheets as database	Simple, familiar storage for candidate data. Trade-off: no real-time sync, limited query performance at scale.
Single dashboard output	Results flow to a UI rather than automated actions (e.g., auto-email). Trade-off: requires manual follow-up, but gives recruiters full control.
